02:44:02.560 --> 02:44:06.000
My name is John Morris,
founder of Wheelchair Travel dot org,

02:44:06.000 --> 02:44:11.760
an accessible travel website that is read
by wheelchair users and disabled people

02:44:11.840 --> 02:44:15.800
from across the United States
and around the world.

02:44:15.880 --> 02:44:19.120
I am a triple amputee and power
wheelchair user.

02:44:19.200 --> 02:44:23.600
I travel frequently, taking
well over 100 flights per year

02:44:23.680 --> 02:44:29.520
and have done so since my first trip
as a wheelchair user ten years ago.

02:44:29.600 --> 02:44:34.440
I encountered many barriers while
traveling throughout the United States.

02:44:34.520 --> 02:44:39.400
None more frustrating than the lack
of accessible ground transportation.

02:44:39.480 --> 02:44:44.360
The lack of wheelchair taxis has left me
stranded for long periods of time,

02:44:44.440 --> 02:44:48.600
in some cases overnight
in a list of cities that includes.

02:44:48.600 --> 02:44:52.200
But not limited to Cleveland. Dallas.

02:44:52.200 --> 02:44:53.840
Los Angeles.

02:44:53.840 --> 02:44:55.960
Orlando. Miami.

02:44:55.960 --> 02:44:58.080
Nashville. Tampa.

02:44:58.080 --> 02:45:01.080
San Diego and Saint Louis.

02:45:01.200 --> 02:45:06.800
I was once forced to sleep overnight
in a gas station parking lot

02:45:06.880 --> 02:45:09.640
over my ten years of disabled travel.

02:45:09.640 --> 02:45:13.600
Rideshare services
have expanded across the country in cities

02:45:13.600 --> 02:45:17.600
both large and small,
taking significant market share

02:45:17.680 --> 02:45:21.840
and leaving traditional taxi companies
at a disadvantage.

02:45:21.920 --> 02:45:26.320
While ADA compliance
among cab companies was poor

02:45:26.320 --> 02:45:30.280
ten years ago,
it is significantly worse now.

02:45:30.360 --> 02:45:34.200
Wheelchair taxis
that previously existed no longer

02:45:34.200 --> 02:45:38.320
do when calling for a wheelchair taxi
in many cities.

02:45:38.400 --> 02:45:43.400
Customers being told
the van is out for repairs.

02:45:43.480 --> 02:45:45.920
Where adapted taxis do exist.

02:45:45.920 --> 02:45:49.400
Most operators
require reservations of 24 hours

02:45:49.400 --> 02:45:54.880
or more in advance and only operate
during normal business hours from 9 a.m.

02:45:54.880 --> 02:45:56.320
to 5 p.m..

02:45:56.320 --> 02:46:00.080
Policies which restrict
the freedom of disabled people.

02:46:00.160 --> 02:46:01.800
Why is this?

02:46:01.800 --> 02:46:06.040
It's because ADA
taxis are not kept in continuous service

02:46:06.120 --> 02:46:11.120
but instead spend the night
at the homes of their daytime drivers.

02:46:11.200 --> 02:46:12.480
A small number of U.S.

02:46:12.480 --> 02:46:16.080
cities, fewer
than ten have gained concessions

02:46:16.080 --> 02:46:20.320
from rideshare operators
to provide accessible services.

02:46:20.400 --> 02:46:24.360
However, those services
rarely operate around the clock.

02:46:24.440 --> 02:46:28.160
With few exceptions,
the availability of wheelchair taxis

02:46:28.240 --> 02:46:33.560
has decreased significantly,
particularly following the pandemic.

02:46:33.640 --> 02:46:34.960
Pricing discrimination

02:46:34.960 --> 02:46:37.960
also serves as a barrier to taxi
transport.

02:46:38.200 --> 02:46:40.000
