03:05:55.400 --> 03:05:58.920
to Gene Editing: The Current and Potential Impact

03:05:58.920 --> 03:06:00.840
of Prenatal Interventions on

03:06:00.840 --> 03:06:03.120
People with Disabilities.

03:06:03.120 --> 03:06:05.840
As Madam Chair mentioned,
this report is the next report

03:06:05.840 --> 03:06:10.840
in NCD’s bioethics series, which
the Policy Team started in 2019.

03:06:10.920 --> 03:06:15.280
We started the series because despite
the growing understanding that disability

03:06:15.280 --> 03:06:18.600
is a normal part of the human experience,
the lives of people

03:06:18.600 --> 03:06:23.080
with disabilities continue to be devalued
in medical decision making.

03:06:23.160 --> 03:06:26.160
In this series,
we've taken on several different topics,

03:06:26.160 --> 03:06:28.480
including organ transplantation.

03:06:28.480 --> 03:06:33.800
physician-assisted suicide, quality-adjusted life years,

03:06:33.880 --> 03:06:37.760
medical futility issues, and started
looking at genetic testing

03:06:37.760 --> 03:06:40.760
primarily through an employment
discrimination lens.

03:06:40.920 --> 03:06:45.720
This next report that you're voting on
today also looks at genetic testing.

03:06:45.800 --> 03:06:48.360
But here we've looked
at prenatal interventions

03:06:48.360 --> 03:06:52.640
that can include a host of technologies,
and applications, ranging

03:06:52.640 --> 03:06:57.040
from fetal surgery to repair of lesion
in utero or a baby with spinal bifida

03:06:57.120 --> 03:07:01.040
to pre-implantation
genetic diagnosis, screening out embryos.

03:07:01.040 --> 03:07:04.120
with certain conditions,
to human heritable genome

03:07:04.120 --> 03:07:09.160
editing to alter the DNA of an embryo,
to modify a genetic trait.

03:07:09.240 --> 03:07:10.920
All prenatal interventions

03:07:10.920 --> 03:07:15.680
ranging from fetal surgery to prenatal
genetic screening, to heritable genome

03:07:15.680 --> 03:07:20.840
editing, hearing unique practical, ethical
and disability rights implications.

03:07:20.920 --> 03:07:24.880
These technologies
required guidance from policy experts,

03:07:24.960 --> 03:07:29.520
scientists, medical providers,
disability and social justice advocates,

03:07:29.600 --> 03:07:33.520
researchers, bioethicists
and other experts.

03:07:33.600 --> 03:07:36.640
The report that we are issuing
now identifies

03:07:36.640 --> 03:07:40.280
the possible impact of these technologies
on the disability community

03:07:40.360 --> 03:07:44.080
gathers input about recommended
policies and practices

03:07:44.160 --> 03:07:47.880
so that any prenatal technology
developed and utilized

03:07:47.960 --> 03:07:51.240
are determined by including people
with disabilities as decision makers

03:07:51.240 --> 03:07:55.440
who have experience living with various
prenatally diagnosed conditions

03:07:55.520 --> 03:07:59.920
and aims to provide recommendations
to answer any prenatal intervention

03:08:00.000 --> 03:08:02.880
do not disproportionately harm people
with disabilities.

03:08:02.880 --> 03:08:06.800
As a historically marginalized population.

03:08:06.880 --> 03:08:10.200
Each report in the series,
including this one, examines how

03:08:10.200 --> 03:08:14.800
these areas are developing as a result
of technological and scientific advances,

03:08:15.000 --> 03:08:18.600
as well as changes
to the law and health care delivery.

03:08:18.680 --> 03:08:20.760
A combination of original research,

03:08:20.760 --> 03:08:24.000
stakeholder and scholar interviews,
literature reviews,

03:08:24.200 --> 03:08:27.080
reviews
and media reports and legal analysis

03:08:27.080 --> 03:08:30.320
